"""
MKT Context Commentary — 1 Chronicles chapters 19–22
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-1chronicles-19-22.py

Ch 19: Ammonite-Aramean war — Hanun's humiliation of David's envoys; ANE honor-shame
        dynamics of beard-shaving and garment-cutting; mercenary chariot coalition;
        Joab's two-front battle strategy; parallels 2 Sam 10.
Ch 20: Fall of Rabbah and Philistine giants — the Chronicler omits Bathsheba/Uriah
        entirely; the Ammonite king's crown as possibly Milcom's; Rephaim giants
        and the 2 Sam 21:19 / 1 Chr 20:5 textual variant on Elhanan's kill.
Ch 21: David's census and the threshing floor — key textual variant: "Satan" in 1 Chr
        vs "the LORD's anger" in 2 Sam 24; development of the adversary figure in
        Second Temple Judaism; ANE threshing floor as sacred/civic space; fire from
        heaven as divine acceptance; the temple site identified.
Ch 22: David prepares for the temple — David's blood-guilt disqualification and
        Solomon's "man of rest" designation; commissioning formula echoing Moses
        to Joshua; ANE quarry labor and corvée; the staggering material quantities
        as hyperbole of royal generosity.

Key decisions:
- mālaʿm in 20:2: could be "their king" or "Milcom" — both are noted
- The 2 Sam 24/1 Chr 21 variant is a key theological discussion point
- The amounts in 22:14 are not literal but magnitudes of generosity in ANE idiom
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRON1 = {
  "19": {
    "1": "<p>1 Chronicles 19 parallels 2 Samuel 10:1-19 almost verbatim. The Chronicler&rsquo;s inclusion of this material (unlike his omission of the Bathsheba-Uriah episode in 2 Sam 11-12) signals his intent: military victories and covenant faithfulness are highlighted; moral failures of David that were already dealt with theologically (the Chronicler&rsquo;s retrojected lesson for the post-exilic community) are suppressed. Nahash the Ammonite had previously shown David kindness — likely during Saul&rsquo;s reign when David was a fugitive (1 Sam 11:1-11 gives the Jabesh-gilead background on Nahash).</p>",
    "2": "<p>David&rsquo;s initiative to send a sympathy delegation to Hanun reflects the ANE practice of royal condolence — a recognized diplomatic courtesy between neighboring states. In ANE diplomacy, mourning envoys carried both personal sympathy and political communication: they represented the king&rsquo;s court, maintained alliances, and could negotiate treaty renewal after a dynastic change. David&rsquo;s act is an offer of covenant continuity with the new Ammonite king.</p>",
    "3": "<p>The Ammonite commanders&rsquo; suspicion that David&rsquo;s envoys are spies (<em>hăḵāḇôd / lěḥāqôr</em> — &ldquo;to honor / to spy out&rdquo;) reflects a standard ANE political paranoia about diplomatic embassies. The verb <em>lāḥāqar</em> (to search/spy out) is the same used of the spies in the wilderness (Num 13:2). The Ammonite response makes a calculated political judgment: the post-David-Nahash alliance is no longer binding, and David&rsquo;s delegation is reframed as a pretext for annexation.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Shaving the beard and cutting the garments at mid-buttock (<em>baḥăṣî</em> = at the middle) were precise acts of ritual humiliation in ANE context. The beard in ancient Israel and surrounding cultures was a symbol of masculine dignity, social status, and covenant identity — cutting another man&rsquo;s beard was among the most degrading acts one person could perform against another (cf. Isa 7:20 where YHWH &ldquo;shaves&rdquo; Assyria as judgment). Exposing the men&rsquo;s lower bodies made them publicly naked — a condition of slaves and captives, not free covenant representatives.</p>",
    "5": "<p>David orders the envoys to remain at Jericho until their beards grow back — a practical act of mercy. The choice of Jericho is significant: it was the first conquered city of Canaan, near the Jordan crossing, an appropriate staging point for men entering from Ammonite territory. The public shame of the men is real and immediate; David&rsquo;s response treats it as a legitimate wound requiring time to heal, not merely a diplomatic incident.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The Ammonites hire a coalition for one thousand talents of silver — an enormous sum. One talent = approximately 32 kg; 1,000 talents = roughly 32 metric tons of silver. ANE military texts confirm the practice of hiring mercenary chariot corps: the Aramean states north of Israel were known exporters of chariot forces. Aram Naharaim (Aram of the Two Rivers, upper Mesopotamia) and Aram Maacah (south of Mt. Hermon) are specific polities confirmed in extrabiblical texts.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Thirty-two thousand chariots is a very large number — likely inflated in the tradition or referring to a broader military force. ANE military records (e.g., the Battle of Qarqar, 853 BCE) cite large chariot coalitions; Shalmaneser III&rsquo;s annals describe Ahab of Israel contributing 2,000 chariots to an anti-Assyrian coalition. Medeba was a Transjordanian city (modern Madaba, Jordan) — the Ammonites marshaled their forces in their own territory east of the Jordan.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Joab commands &ldquo;the whole army and its warriors&rdquo; (<em>gibbôrê haḥayil</em>) — the professional warrior class distinct from the general levy. The Chronicler here uses the same term used of David&rsquo;s &ldquo;mighty men&rdquo; (1 Chr 11:10-47). The professional standing army David had organized around a core of veteran warriors (the &ldquo;three&rdquo; and the &ldquo;thirty&rdquo;) represents the institutionalization of Israelite military capacity first developed under Saul.</p>",
    "9": "<p>The Ammonites position themselves at the city gate while the Aramean mercenaries deploy in the open field — a classic pincer formation. ANE siege warfare doctrine placed city defenders at the gate to prevent retreat while allied field forces engaged the attacking army from behind. Joab immediately recognizes the tactical problem: two separate fronts requiring split command.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Joab&rsquo;s tactical response — selecting elite troops (<em>bāḥûr</em> — the chosen, best-quality warriors) for the Aramean front — reflects the standard ANE principle of concentrating quality forces against the primary threat. The Aramean chariot force was the greater tactical danger; the Ammonite infantry at the gate could be managed by a secondary force under Abishai.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Joab places his brother Abishai in command of the secondary force facing the Ammonites. The coordination of two-pronged operations under brothers reflects the family-based command structure of early Israelite armies. Abishai son of Zeruiah appears repeatedly in David&rsquo;s narratives as a capable but sometimes excessively violent commander (2 Sam 16:9-10; 19:21-22); here he serves a supporting role under Joab.</p>",
    "12": "<p>Joab&rsquo;s tactical agreement with Abishai creates mutual reinforcement logic: if either front collapses, the other commander will disengage and assist. This reflects ANE military doctrine of interior lines — a smaller force maintaining communication between two fronts. The agreement is verbal, direct, and practical; no appeal to divine oracles before battle, which distinguishes this military narrative from earlier holy-war accounts.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;May the LORD do what is right in his eyes&rdquo; (<em>ṭôḇ bĕʿênāyw yaʿăśeh</em>) — Joab&rsquo;s battle exhortation is theologically significant coming from this pragmatic general. It subordinates military strategy to divine sovereignty, echoing the theological framework of Deuteronomic history: ultimate outcomes belong to YHWH even when human strategy is maximally employed. The phrase echoes 2 Sam 10:12 and is a version of the holy-war submission formula.</p>",
    "14": "<p>The Arameans flee before Joab. In ANE military narratives, the flight of allies was among the most devastating tactical events — it demoralized the remaining forces and eliminated the pincer advantage. The Chronicler notes simply that they fled without attribution of divine cause — the reader is expected to connect Joab&rsquo;s prayer (v13) to the outcome. Narrative economy: the theological interpretation is implicit.</p>",
    "15": "<p>When the Ammonites see the Arameans flee, they retreat to their city walls — a standard ANE defensive response. The city gates functioned as defensive choke points; once the field forces were routed, the city-gate position became untenable and the fallback was the fortified city. Joab prudently returns to Jerusalem rather than besieging Rabbah immediately — a strategically sound decision given the Aramean threat has not been fully resolved.</p>",
    "16": "<p>The Aramean response — summoning reinforcements from &ldquo;beyond the Euphrates&rdquo; (<em>mēʿēber hannāhār</em>) — reveals the extent of Hadadezer&rsquo;s Aramean coalition. Shophach (Shobach in 2 Sam 10:16) as commander of Hadadezer&rsquo;s forces is consistent with what we know of Hadadezer of Zobah as a major Aramean power in the tenth century BCE. The northern Aramean coalition extended into upper Mesopotamia.</p>",
    "17": "<p>David personally crosses the Jordan to lead the engagement — a detail emphasizing his direct military leadership in the climactic battle. Crossing the Jordan was logistically significant: the Jordan was a real military barrier, and David&rsquo;s decision to cross and engage the Arameans in their own territory (across the Euphrates frontier zone) is an aggressive strategic choice rather than defensive waiting.</p>",
    "18": "<p>The numbers of the Aramean casualties — seven thousand chariot fighters and forty thousand infantry — reflect the conventions of ANE battle reports where round or large numbers signal the totality of the defeat rather than precise counts. The killing of Shophach the commander is the key strategic result: the Aramean alliance loses its military leadership, which precipitates the peace negotiations of v19.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Hadadezer&rsquo;s vassal kings sue for peace with David and become his subjects. The political outcome — Aramean client-kingdoms passing from Hadadezer&rsquo;s sphere to David&rsquo;s — matches the territorial expansion described in 1 Chr 18:3-8. The Chronicler&rsquo;s theological point: David&rsquo;s kingdom expands not through his own ambition but through YHWH&rsquo;s providential arrangement of military outcomes, making Israel the dominant regional power in the Levant.</p>"
  },
  "20": {
    "1": "<p>&ldquo;In the spring, at the time when kings went to war&rdquo; (<em>lĕtĕšûḇat haššānâ</em>, lit. &ldquo;at the return of the year&rdquo;) — a conventional ANE formula marking the spring campaign season. After winter rains ended (roughly April-May), roads became passable for armies and logistics, and the harvest was approaching. This exact phrase (in 2 Sam 11:1) introduces the Bathsheba-Uriah narrative, which the Chronicler notably omits. By jumping directly to the capture of Rabbah, the Chronicler silently elides David&rsquo;s greatest moral failure while preserving the military accomplishment.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The Ammonite king&rsquo;s crown weighed a talent of gold (about 75 lbs/34 kg) — too heavy for a human to actually wear, suggesting either a symbolic/votive crown or a crown placed on a divine statue. The Hebrew <em>malkām</em> can be translated either &ldquo;their king&rdquo; (Hanun) or as the proper name Milcom/Molech, the Ammonite national deity (1 Kgs 11:5). The LXX reads &ldquo;Milcom,&rdquo; and many scholars follow this: David takes the crown from the Ammonite god&rsquo;s statue as a trophy, symbolizing YHWH&rsquo;s victory over the competing deity.</p>",
    "3": "<p>David&rsquo;s treatment of the Rabbah inhabitants — put to work with saws, iron picks, and axes — describes forced labor rather than execution (the Hebrew can be read either way; 1 Chr 20:3 uses <em>wayyāśar</em> = he sawed; 2 Sam 12:31 also mentions similar treatment). The use of conquered populations for building projects was standard ANE practice: the Assyrians and Babylonians routinely employed captured peoples in state construction. David&rsquo;s action places the Ammonite population in the corvée system — labor obligation to the state.</p>",
    "4": "<p>The Philistine wars at Gezer — Sibbecai the Hushathite killing Sippai (= Saph in 2 Sam 21:18). Gezer was a strategically crucial city on the western approach to Jerusalem, controlling the valley road from the coast. It remained semi-independent through much of the monarchy; Solomon received it from Pharaoh as a dowry (1 Kgs 9:16). These Philistine giant-slaying episodes were likely originally part of a hero-list tradition celebrating David&rsquo;s warriors.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The textual variant: 1 Chr 20:5 attributes the kill to &ldquo;Elhanan son of Jair&rdquo; who killed &ldquo;Lahmi the brother of Goliath the Gittite,&rdquo; while 2 Sam 21:19 reads &ldquo;Elhanan son of Jaare-oregim&rdquo; who killed &ldquo;Goliath the Gittite&rdquo; (without &ldquo;the brother of&rdquo;). Chronicles appears to harmonize the apparent conflict with 1 Sam 17 (where David kills Goliath) by adding &ldquo;the brother of.&rdquo; This is likely a scribal correction in the Chronicler&rsquo;s source; the earlier tradition in Samuel preserves the more difficult reading.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The giant with six fingers and six toes (twelve digits per hand/foot) at Gath — polydactyly, a rare congenital condition. The association of this anomaly with the Rephaim (pre-Israelite giant peoples of Canaan, Deut 2:10-12; 3:11; Gen 14:5) may reflect a tradition of unusual physical traits among this group. Goliath&rsquo;s spear &ldquo;like a weaver&rsquo;s rod&rdquo; (1 Sam 17:7) and his height (6 cubits and a span = approximately 9 feet, or 4.5 cubits = approximately 6.5 feet in some manuscripts) are part of this warrior-giant tradition.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Jonathan son of Shimea (David&rsquo;s brother) kills the six-fingered giant. The naming of David&rsquo;s nephew as the hero here fits a pattern: David&rsquo;s inner family circle participates in the giant-slaying tradition, which the narrator connects with the broader elimination of the Rephaim threat to Israel. The Rephaim as supernatural or semi-divine beings appear in Ugaritic texts (<em>rpum</em>) as a class of deified warrior-heroes; their ANE background gives the Israelite tradition a demythologizing edge.</p>",
    "8": "<p>The summary formula — &ldquo;these were the descendants of the Rephaim in Gath, and they fell at the hands of David and his warriors&rdquo; — closes the Philistine war episodes. The Chronicler uses this unit to demonstrate the completeness of David&rsquo;s military achievement: all major enemies (Moab, Aram, Edom, Ammon, Philistia) have been subdued. The rest David achieves through warfare becomes the pre-condition for Solomon&rsquo;s temple-building era of peace.</p>"
  },
  "21": {
    "1": "<p>The most significant theological textual variant between Samuel and Chronicles: 1 Chr 21:1 reads &ldquo;Satan (<em>śāṭān</em>) stood up against Israel and incited David,&rdquo; while 2 Sam 24:1 reads &ldquo;the anger of the LORD was kindled against Israel, and he incited David.&rdquo; In Job 1-2, <em>haśśāṭān</em> (with the definite article) is a prosecutorial figure in the divine council, not yet the personified cosmic enemy of later tradition. The Chronicler (ca. 400 BCE) may reflect the post-exilic development of the adversary figure under Persian influence (Ahriman / Angra Mainyu) or may simply be distinguishing proximate cause (the adversarial spirit) from ultimate cause (YHWH&rsquo;s sovereignty), protecting the divine character from direct causation of sin.</p>",
    "2": "<p>David&rsquo;s command to count Israel &ldquo;from Beersheba to Dan&rdquo; — the standard formula for the full extent of the land, here in south-to-north order (the more common formula &ldquo;Dan to Beersheba&rdquo; goes north to south). The census represented both military capability assessment and assertion of royal sovereignty over the population. In ANE contexts, censuses functioned as precursors to taxation and conscription; the Davidic census is theologically problematic because it substitutes trust in human military numbers for trust in YHWH, the divine warrior who won Israel&rsquo;s battles regardless of numbers (cf. Gideon&rsquo;s 300, Judg 7:2-7).</p>",
    "3": "<p>Joab&rsquo;s objection inverts the census logic: &ldquo;May the LORD multiply his people a hundredfold!&rdquo; — the blessing formula of Deut 1:11 and 28:63. The true measure of Israel&rsquo;s strength is YHWH&rsquo;s promise, not the census count. Joab, who is generally portrayed as a pragmatic military man willing to cross moral boundaries (the killing of Abner, Absalom, Amasa), here displays unexpected theological clarity: the census represents a failure of covenant trust. The Chronicler amplifies Joab&rsquo;s objection compared to 2 Sam 24:3.</p>",
    "4": "<p>David overrides Joab&rsquo;s objection — a significant narrative detail. In the sequence of events, royal command overrides prophetic/prudential counsel. The Deuteronomic ideal was a king who heeded the priests and prophets; David&rsquo;s insistence here anticipates the prophetic critique of royal self-sufficiency. Joab&rsquo;s tour covers &ldquo;all Israel&rdquo; — the comprehensive nature of the census is both its military rationale and its theological offense.</p>",
    "5": "<p>The census numbers differ from 2 Sam 24:9: Chronicles gives 1,100,000 for Israel (vs 800,000 in Samuel) and 470,000 for Judah (vs 500,000 in Samuel). These discrepancies are unresolved in the textual tradition; possible explanations include different counting methods, different territorial definitions, or different transmission histories. The Chronicler&rsquo;s numbers may reflect a military-eligible population count at a different point in David&rsquo;s reign.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Levi and Benjamin excluded from the count. The Levites were YHWH&rsquo;s holy tribe, set apart for tabernacle/temple service and not subject to military conscription (Num 1:47-49). The Benjaminite exclusion is unexplained in the text; some suggest Benjamin&rsquo;s proximity to the sanctuary at Gibeon made including them in a military census inappropriate. Joab&rsquo;s exclusion of these tribes reflects residual respect for covenantal structures even when executing an order he opposed.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;God was displeased (<em>wayyēraʿ</em>) with this and struck Israel.&rdquo; The census is immediately judged — before even the prophetic confrontation through Gad. The moral causation is direct: the sin is named, divine displeasure follows, and Israel (the people David was supposed to protect) bears the initial consequences. This pattern — the community suffering for the king&rsquo;s sin — reflects the ANE royal ideology where the king&rsquo;s covenant standing determined the whole community&rsquo;s standing before the deity.</p>",
    "8": "<p>David&rsquo;s immediate confession: &ldquo;I have sinned greatly by doing this.&rdquo; The confessional formula (<em>ḥāṭāʾtî mĕʾōd</em>) echoes Saul&rsquo;s more self-serving confession (1 Sam 15:24) but David&rsquo;s is direct and unqualified. David adds: &ldquo;I have acted very foolishly&rdquo; (<em>nisskaltî mĕʾōd</em>) — acknowledging both the moral and the practical dimensions of the sin. David&rsquo;s post-sin response consistently involves immediate acknowledgment without evasion, which the Chronicler (and the broader OT tradition) presents as a distinguishing characteristic.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Gad is identified as &ldquo;David&rsquo;s seer&rdquo; (<em>ḥōzeh Dāwîd</em>) — a court prophet attached to the royal household. The institution of the court prophet/seer who delivers divine communications to the king is well-attested in ANE: Mari texts from 18th-century BCE Mesopotamia preserve prophetic messages delivered to kings, often involving oracular choices and divine judgment. Gad appears several times in the David narrative (1 Sam 22:5; 2 Sam 24:11-19; 1 Chr 21:9-19; 29:29).</p>",
    "10": "<p>Three options for punishment — the tripartite divine ultimatum is a formal structure giving the recipient a choice. The three punishments (famine, enemy defeat, plague) correspond to the curses of Deut 28:21-25: pestilence, defeat before enemies, famine. The three-year famine, three-month enemy rout, and three-day plague represent decreasing duration but increasing intensity — David is given a real choice with genuine stakes.</p>",
    "11": "<p>Gad as oral messenger: the prophet does not write but speaks the divine word directly to the king. The prophetic communication chain — YHWH to prophet to king — preserves the mediatorial structure of Israelite covenant theology. Unlike ANE divination (entrails reading, celestial omens) which operated through technical specialists interpreting physical signs, Israelite prophecy was verbal, personal, and direct: YHWH communicates in words through a human messenger.</p>",
    "12": "<p>The three-day plague &ldquo;with the LORD&rsquo;s angel ravaging every part of Israel&rdquo; — the pestilence option is simultaneously the most intense (70,000 die) and, as David seems to calculate, the one that keeps Israel in YHWH&rsquo;s hands rather than in the hands of human enemies. ANE plagues were attributed to divine agency — the Mesopotamian god Erra/Nergal was specifically the god of pestilence. Chronicles frames the angel as YHWH&rsquo;s direct agent, not an independent demonic force.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;Let me fall into the LORD&rsquo;s hands, because his mercy (<em>raḥămāyw</em>) is very great&rdquo; — David&rsquo;s choice reveals his theological conviction that divine punishment is preferable to human punishment because YHWH&rsquo;s essential character includes mercy (<em>raḥămîm</em>, from <em>reḥem</em>, womb-like compassion). This is a remarkable statement of faith within the context of accepting punishment: David trusts the character of the one who is punishing him. It anticipates the Psalms&rsquo; appeals to divine mercy even in the midst of deserved discipline (Ps 51:1; 130:3-4).</p>",
    "14": "<p>Seventy thousand die in the plague. The number echoes the seventy elders of Israel (Exod 24:1), the seventy nations (Gen 10), and Ahab&rsquo;s seventy sons (2 Kgs 10:1) — the number of totality and completion. The death toll is the full weight of covenant curse for royal sin executed at the national level. The post-exilic community reading this text would recognize in the plague an analogue to the Babylonian destruction — the same pattern of divine punishment following covenant failure.</p>",
    "15": "<p>God sends an angel to destroy Jerusalem but then &ldquo;relented&rdquo; (<em>wayyinnāḥem</em>) from the disaster. The verb <em>nāḥam</em> (H5162) describes divine grief and reversal — used of God&rsquo;s &ldquo;regret&rdquo; in Gen 6:6, Jer 18:7-10, and Amos 7:3. The angel standing &ldquo;between heaven and earth&rdquo; over the threshing floor is a liminal figure occupying the boundary between the divine and earthly realms — the same spatial register as the ladder in Gen 28:12. The LORD&rsquo;s command &ldquo;Enough! Lower your hand&rdquo; (<em>raḇ hārep yādĕḵā</em>) echoes divine self-restraint in judgment.</p>",
    "16": "<p>David and the elders, clothed in sackcloth, prostrate themselves before the angel of the LORD. Sackcloth (<em>śaq</em>) was the material of mourning and penitence in the ANE — coarse goat-hair cloth worn against the skin as a sign of grief, humiliation, and petition. The visual of the king and elders in sackcloth before the divine warrior with drawn sword is a complete reversal of royal posture: the military sovereign who took the census is now prostrate before the heavenly army commander.</p>",
    "17": "<p>David&rsquo;s intercession takes the corporate blame entirely on himself: &ldquo;These sheep — what have they done?&rdquo; The shepherd-flock metaphor for king-people is standard ANE royal ideology; Mesopotamian and Egyptian royal titles include &ldquo;shepherd of the people.&rdquo; David&rsquo;s prayer inverts the ANE royal claim: rather than asserting his shepherd-authority, he acknowledges his shepherd-responsibility. The language anticipates Ezekiel&rsquo;s critique of false shepherds who exploit rather than protect the flock (Ezek 34).</p>",
    "18": "<p>The angel of the LORD directs Gad to tell David to build an altar on the threshing floor of Ornan the Jebusite. The threshing floor (<em>gōren</em>) was a significant site in ANE culture: elevated, open, wind-exposed, used for grain processing, and often associated with sacred activity (Gen 50:10-11; Ruth 3:6; Hos 9:1). Threshing floors on heights near cities could double as open-air cultic sites. Ornan&rsquo;s floor on the hill north of the city of David is the future Temple Mount (2 Chr 3:1).</p>",
    "19": "<p>David goes up &ldquo;in obedience to Gad&rsquo;s word, spoken in the LORD&rsquo;s name.&rdquo; The prophetic word carries divine authority — obedience to the prophet is obedience to YHWH. This principle undergirds the entire prophetic institution: the prophet does not speak his own words but YHWH&rsquo;s, and therefore compliance with the prophetic instruction is theologically equivalent to compliance with the divine command (Deut 18:15-20).</p>",
    "20": "<p>Ornan threshing wheat when he turns and sees the angel — the harvest scene grounds the narrative in agricultural reality. Ornan&rsquo;s four sons hide themselves in fear. The threshing floor as the site of the divine-human encounter follows a pattern: Ruth meets Boaz at the threshing floor (Ruth 3), the judges receive divine communications in agricultural contexts (Gideon at the winepress, Judg 6:11). The ordinary site of agricultural labor becomes the site of sacred encounter.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Ornan bows face to the ground before David. The prostration (<em>wayyišṭaḥû ʾappayw ʾarṣâ</em>) is the full submission posture — both ceremonial respect for the king and probably terror at David&rsquo;s arrival in the context of the recent plague. Ornan as a Jebusite — the pre-Israelite population of Jerusalem — provides the background for the Davidic purchase: the sacred site had Jebusite associations before the Israelite cult claimed it, a fact the narrative carefully validates through legal purchase.</p>",
    "22": "<p>David requests the threshing floor &ldquo;at full price (<em>bĕkeṣep māle&rsquo;)</em>&rdquo; — the insistence on full market value is legally and theologically significant. In ANE property law, the price established the legal title and removed any claim of charitable gift or spoliation. David&rsquo;s purchase echoes Abraham&rsquo;s insistence on paying full price for the Machpelah burial cave (Gen 23:9), establishing undisputed ownership of a sacred site. No future generation can claim the Temple Mount was taken unjustly.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Ornan&rsquo;s generous offer — threshing floor, oxen, threshing sledges, and wheat — free of charge. The offer follows ANE gift-protocol: the subordinate offers everything to the king as a gesture of loyalty. The items Ornan offers are precisely what is needed for the altar sacrifice: oxen as the burnt offering, threshing sledges as the wood fuel, wheat as the grain offering. The provision is complete and providential — everything needed for the altar is present at the site.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;I will not take what is yours for the LORD, or offer burnt offerings that cost me nothing.&rdquo; David&rsquo;s refusal is a foundational principle of authentic worship: the offering must cost the worshiper something real. This is not merely ethical punctiliousness but theological conviction — sacrifice that involves no loss is not sacrifice but performance. The principle applies with force to the post-exilic community&rsquo;s experience: rebuilding the temple required genuine material sacrifice from returned exiles.</p>",
    "25": "<p>David pays 600 shekels of gold. The 2 Sam 24:24 parallel records 50 shekels of silver for the oxen and threshing floor alone — the discrepancy is large. Most interpreters explain it as different transactions: 2 Samuel records the immediate purchase of the threshing floor and oxen; 1 Chronicles records the purchase of the entire Temple Mount site. The higher price in Chronicles (gold vs silver; 600 vs 50 shekels) fits the grander scope of what the Chronicler understands was acquired.</p>",
    "26": "<p>David builds the altar and YHWH answers by fire from heaven on the burnt offering. Divine fire as the sign of accepted sacrifice is a recurring motif: Lev 9:24 (fire descends at the inauguration of the Mosaic tabernacle worship), Elijah on Carmel (1 Kgs 18:38), and 2 Chr 7:1 (fire at the temple dedication). The fire signals divine presence and approval — YHWH claiming the altar as his own. The threshing floor of Ornan is thereby authenticated as the true locus of YHWH&rsquo;s covenant presence.</p>",
    "27": "<p>The LORD commands the angel to sheathe his sword. The drawn sword throughout the plague narrative signified active divine judgment; its sheathing signals the end of the punitive phase. In ANE iconography, divine warrior figures are depicted with unsheathed weapons in contexts of judgment; the sheathed weapon is the posture of sovereign rest after victorious judgment. The command sequence — YHWH commands the angel to stop — asserts YHWH&rsquo;s absolute sovereignty over the divine warrior figure.</p>",
    "28": "<p>David continues to sacrifice at Ornan&rsquo;s threshing floor rather than returning to the tabernacle at Gibeon. This establishes a new cultic center — not by royal decree but by divine appointment through the plague-and-fire sequence. The theological logic: YHWH himself chose this site by directing the angel there, commanding the altar, and sending fire. The tabernacle location becomes secondary; the temple site is divinely designated.</p>",
    "29": "<p>The tabernacle of Moses and its bronze altar of burnt offering were at Gibeon at the high place. The Chronicler acknowledges the dual cultic situation: there was a legitimate Mosaic altar at Gibeon (2 Chr 1:3-6 shows Solomon sacrificing there before the temple) and a new altar at the threshing floor site. The explanation for why David does not return to Gibeon (terror before the angel&rsquo;s sword) provides the transitional logic for the shift from Gibeon to Jerusalem as the cultic center.</p>",
    "30": "<p>David&rsquo;s fear of the drawn sword prevents him from consulting YHWH at Gibeon. The angel&rsquo;s presence between the threshing floor and Gibeon creates a spiritual obstacle — David cannot pass under the drawn sword to reach the tabernacle. This narrative explanation for why David stays at the new altar site is the Chronicler&rsquo;s way of saying: YHWH himself redirected the locus of sacrifice from Gibeon to the Temple Mount. David&rsquo;s obedience to this redirection is the act of faithfulness that the temple-site selection requires.</p>"
  },
  "22": {
    "1": "<p>David&rsquo;s declaration: &ldquo;This is to be the house of the LORD God, and this is the altar of burnt offering for Israel.&rdquo; The demonstrative <em>zeh</em> (this) is emphatic — the specific threshing floor is named as the permanent cultic site. The Chronicler understands this declaration as the direct consequence of the plague-altar sequence: David&rsquo;s recognition that YHWH has designated this place. 2 Chr 3:1 later confirms it as &ldquo;Mount Moriah&rdquo; — linking the temple to the Abrahamic sacrifice site (Gen 22:2).</p>",
    "2": "<p>David assembles the <em>gērîm</em> — the foreign residents (<em>gēr</em>, H1616 = a resident alien with protected but non-citizen status) — as stonecutters. The use of resident aliens for skilled construction labor reflects both ANE practice and Israelite social law: the <em>gēr</em> had legal protections (Exod 23:9; Deut 24:17-18) but was subject to conscription for state labor projects (cf. Solomon&rsquo;s later forced levy of all Israel, 1 Kgs 5:13-18). The Solomonic temple was built with significant foreign labor.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Iron for nails and bronze in vast quantities — David&rsquo;s iron procurement is significant because iron was still a relatively controlled material in early Iron Age Canaan. The Philistines had maintained a near-monopoly on iron smithing (1 Sam 13:19-22); David&rsquo;s campaigns against Philistia broke this monopoly. The Chronicler&rsquo;s emphasis on David stockpiling iron reflects the historical reality that the Iron Age transitioned partly through Davidic military success.</p>",
    "4": "<p>Cedar from the Sidonians and Tyrians — the Lebanon cedar trade was one of the most significant resource relationships in the ANE. Lebanon cedar (<em>ʾerez hallĕḇānôn</em>) was prized throughout the Near East for its durability, straight grain, and fragrance; it was used in Egypt, Mesopotamia, and the Levant for palace and temple construction. The Phoenician trading cities of Sidon and Tyre controlled the timber trade as their primary economic resource. David&rsquo;s establishment of this supply relationship is the pre-condition for Solomon&rsquo;s treaty with Hiram of Tyre (1 Kgs 5:1-12).</p>",
    "5": "<p>David&rsquo;s self-assessment: &ldquo;My son Solomon is young (<em>naʿar</em>) and inexperienced (<em>raḵ</em>).&rdquo; The Hebrew <em>naʿar</em> covers a wide range (infant to young adult) but here emphasizes inexperience with statecraft; <em>raḵ</em> (tender, inexperienced) suggests both youth and the lack of hardening that comes from years of war and governance. David&rsquo;s logic: the temple project requires preparation precisely because Solomon will not yet have the resources, relationships, or experience to acquire them independently.</p>",
    "6": "<p>David&rsquo;s charge to Solomon begins here — a private father-to-son commissioning speech that has no parallel in 1-2 Kings. The Chronicler develops this as a theological centrepiece: before his death, David gives Solomon the theological rationale for the temple, the divine word disqualifying David, and the materials inventory. The private charge sets up the public charge in chs 28-29. ANE royal inscriptions often include the deceased king&rsquo;s instructions for temple maintenance as a form of legitimation for the successor.</p>",
    "7": "<p>&ldquo;It was my deepest desire (<em>ʿim lĕḇāḇî</em> — &ldquo;with my heart&rdquo;) to build a house for the name of the LORD.&rdquo; The phrase &ldquo;for the name of the LORD&rdquo; (<em>lĕšēm YHWH</em>) is Deuteronomic theology: YHWH does not literally dwell in the temple but his <em>šēm</em> (name = presence, authority, character) is placed there (Deut 12:5, 11; 1 Kgs 8:29). The &ldquo;name&rdquo; theology guards against crude identification of YHWH with a localized deity — he is present in the temple representatively, not spatially confined.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;You have shed much blood (<em>dāmîm rabbîm</em>) and fought many wars — you are not to build a house for my name.&rdquo; The blood-guilt principle: a builder of the LORD&rsquo;s house cannot be a man of blood. The concern is not merely ritual impurity (blood as defiling) but symbolic-theological fitness — the house of the God of peace requires a man of peace as its builder. The ANE parallel: Gudea of Lagash&rsquo;s temple-building inscriptions emphasize the builder&rsquo;s ritual purity and divine election; the wrong kind of person building a temple was a theological problem.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Solomon&rsquo;s name (<em>Šĕlōmōh</em>) is connected etymologically to <em>šālôm</em> (peace) — &ldquo;his name will be Solomon (Peace), and I will give Israel peace and quiet during his reign.&rdquo; The naming theology is explicit: the builder&rsquo;s identity must match the character of what he builds. ANE temple-builders were understood as bringing their character to the sacred space — the god who accepted the temple accepted the builder. Solomon&rsquo;s &ldquo;rest&rdquo; (<em>mĕnûḥâ</em>) is the condition YHWH promised for life in the land (Deut 12:10-11).</p>",
    "10": "<p>&ldquo;He will be my son and I will be his father&rdquo; — the adoption formula from the Davidic covenant (2 Sam 7:14; Ps 2:7). In ANE royal ideology, the king was understood as the god&rsquo;s son in a functional sense — representing the deity on earth, executing divine will, maintaining divine order. The Israelite version of this is covenantal rather than ontological: Solomon is YHWH&rsquo;s son by covenant relationship, not by divine generation. David transmits this covenant promise directly to Solomon, making the chain of Davidic covenant continuity explicit.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The blessing formula &ldquo;May the LORD be with you&rdquo; (<em>YHWH ʿimmāḵ</em>) is the standard covenantal accompaniment formula — the same blessing given to Joshua (Josh 1:5; Deut 31:8) and to Gideon (Judg 6:12). David is passing on both a task and a covenantal relationship. The success of the temple project depends not on Solomon&rsquo;s skill or resources alone but on YHWH&rsquo;s active presence. The formula grounds the entire enterprise in relational theology rather than royal achievement.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;May the LORD give you wisdom (<em>śekel</em>) and discernment (<em>ûḇînâ</em>) when he puts you in charge of Israel.&rdquo; The prayer for wisdom echoes the later Solomonic tradition of 1 Kgs 3:5-14 (Solomon&rsquo;s dream at Gibeon) and Prov 1:1-7 (where Solomon is the patron of wisdom). <em>Śekel</em> (prudence, insight) and <em>bînâ</em> (understanding, discernment) together represent practical and theoretical wisdom — both needed for governing and for the complex management of a temple construction project.</p>",
    "13": "<p>&ldquo;You will succeed if you carefully follow the statutes and ordinances the LORD commanded Moses for Israel.&rdquo; The conditional success formula echoes the Joshua commissioning (Josh 1:7-8) almost verbatim — the same book of the law, the same requirement to observe it carefully. David frames Solomon&rsquo;s kingship in the Deuteronomic mold: royal success is not a function of military or administrative genius but of covenant faithfulness. The Torah is the charter for the Davidic monarchy.</p>",
    "14": "<p>&ldquo;In my distress (<em>bĕʿōnî</em>) I have prepared one hundred thousand talents of gold, a million talents of silver...&rdquo; The quantities are hyperbolic in the extreme — 100,000 talents of gold would be approximately 3,750 tons; the total silver would be far larger. ANE royal inscriptions routinely use hyperbolic quantities to express magnificence and generosity: Assyrian annals record tribute and tribute-lists in inflated terms. The Chronicler&rsquo;s point is theological: David&rsquo;s preparation was proportionate to the grandeur of what YHWH deserves, not to any literal accounting.</p>",
    "15": "<p>The workforce inventory — stonecutters, masons, carpenters, craftsmen in every material. The Chronicler&rsquo;s David is presented as the Moses of the temple construction: just as Moses was given skilled artisans filled with the Spirit of God for the tabernacle (Exod 31:1-11; 35:30-36:1), David assembles and prepares a comparable workforce for the temple. The template for sacred construction is always: divine design, human craftsmanship, divine enabling.</p>",
    "16": "<p>&ldquo;Arise and get to work! The LORD be with you.&rdquo; The final charge is a commissioning formula combining command and blessing — the same structure as Moses&rsquo;s charge to the assembly before the tabernacle construction (Exod 36:2) and YHWH&rsquo;s charge to Joshua (Josh 1:6-7). The work of building the divine dwelling is not human initiative but divine commission executed through human obedience. David transmits this covenantal framework intact to Solomon.</p>",
    "17": "<p>David charges the leaders of Israel to support Solomon — the collective leadership structure of the Chronicler&rsquo;s David. Unlike the Samuel narrative where David rules more individually, the Chronicler consistently presents a David who builds coalitions and delegates: the Levitical appointments, the military commanders, the tribal leaders. The call to &ldquo;support&rdquo; (<em>ʿizrû</em>, from <em>ʿāzar</em> = to help, support) Solomon is both political (loyalty pledge) and practical (resource provision).</p>",
    "18": "<p>&ldquo;Is not the LORD your God with you? Has he not given you rest on every side?&rdquo; David&rsquo;s rhetorical argument to the leaders invokes the accomplished military rest as the theological condition for temple-building. The ANE connection: temple construction was a royal prerogative exercised in a time of peace — you could not build a divine house while fighting wars. The rest David has achieved through military campaigns is now the theological platform for the building project. The inhabitants of the land have been &ldquo;handed over&rdquo; (<em>nittĕnâ hāʾāreṣ</em>) — language of covenant gift.</p>",
    "19": "<p>&ldquo;Devote your whole heart and soul (<em>nĕpešḵem</em>) to seeking (<em>liḏrōš</em>) the LORD your God.&rdquo; The Deuteronomic phrase &ldquo;with all your heart and soul&rdquo; (Deut 6:5; 10:12; 11:13; 26:16) represents the covenant ideal of total orientation toward YHWH. The verb <em>dāraš</em> (to seek, inquire of) is specifically the vocabulary of cultic inquiry and devoted pursuit of YHWH — the opposite of seeking the Baals (2 Chr 17:3-4). The construction of the sanctuary is itself an act of &ldquo;seeking&rdquo; — making space for the divine presence in the midst of the people.</p>"
  }
}

def main():
    c = load_comm('mkt-context', '1chronicles')
    merge_comm(c, CHRON1)
    save_comm('mkt-context', '1chronicles', c)
    count = sum(len(v) for v in CHRON1.values())
    print(f'1chronicles mkt-context: wrote {count} verses for ch 19-22')

if __name__ == '__main__':
    main()
